	<td rowspan="2" valign="top"><a name="1"></a><i><h2><b><u>Benj Wu</u></b></h2></i>
	<p>Senior Master Benj Wu is a 6th Degree Black Belt and our Chief Instructor of	Cheung's Taekwondo&reg;, Oakville. He has been Grand Master Cheung's martial	art pupil since October, 1973 in Kalamazoo, Michigan. He is Grand Master	Cheung's 1st disciple in White Eyebrow Taoist Kung-Fu as well as Taekwondo.</p>
	<p>When Grand Master Cheung opened his fi rst Taekwondo School in Brampton,	Senior Master Wu helped teach on Monday and Wednesday nights so that	Grand Master Cheung could teach the Taekwondo program at the Brampton YM-YWCA. Senior Master Wu has been Grand Master Cheung's most senior student in Cheung's Taekwondo&reg; as well as his best friend for over 33 years.</p>
	<p>He went with Grand Master Cheung to Iowa, U.S.A. for his cover story in	the Taekwondo Times magazine for the May issue in 1987 and was featured on the cover with Grand Master Cheung as well as published his article in the November issue of 1990.</p>
	<p>Senior Master Wu studied Judo and Shotokan Karate for a period of 2 years each, in the State of Oregon prior to meeting Grand Master Cheung in Michigan at	Western Michigan University. Grand Master Cheung was in his 3rd year in the	Undergraduate program while Senior Master Wu was accepted into the M.A.	program in the Department of Psychology.</p>
	<p>He holds the Level of a 1st Class National Referee as well as a Level 2 National	Instructor certifi cation by Taekwondo Canada. He has served as the Chairman of the Refereeing Committee of the Ontario Taekwondo Association and developed	an Ontario wide referee training system for the WTF competition rules. He graduated as a 3rd Class International Referee in Puerto Rico in 1990 and has been a 2nd Class International Referee certifi ed by the World Taekwondo	Federation, Seoul, Korea. He traveled extensively especially in our Pan American Region with Grand Master Cheung offi ciating at the Pan American Taekwondo Championships and various championships sanctioned by the Pan American Taekwondo Union. He was elected as the 1st Vice President of the Ontario Taekwondo Association on May 31st, 2003.</p>
	<p>Senior Master Wu has been teaching & developing Cheung's Taekwondo&reg; program in Oakville for over 28 years. He has produced provincial and national competitors such as Mr. Scott Madden (Canadian National Bronze Medalist, 1983), Miss Andrea Cooke (Canadian National Champion, 1985), and Miss Julie Anceriz (Ontario Provincial and Canadian National Silver Medalist, 2001).</p>
	<p>He is a recipient of the 30th Anniversary Award today at the 2007 Inner Club Tournament.</p>	</td>
